{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01MTQcPAnFByjZtoan3wCrvN","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The logs directory only has GC logs, not the regular application logs in JSON format. This means Elasticsearch is writing its application logs to stdout, not to files in `/usr/share/elasticsearch/logs/`.\n\nIn recent Elasticsearch Docker images, the default logging configuration uses `log4j2.properties` that writes to stdout (appender.console) and may not write to file appenders by default. Let me check.\n\nActually, in ES 8.x Docker images, the default logging is configured to write to the `console` (stdout) appender. The file appenders are disabled in the Docker variant. So the JSON log files won't appear in the logs directory.\nI need to reconfigure the logging for Filebeat to capture ES logs. I could either configure Elasticsearch to write to file appenders by creating a log4j2.properties override in a ConfigMap, or I could have Filebeat collect logs directly from stdout by mounting the container logs from the host filesystem, though that would require node-level mounts rather than a sidecar pattern. The ConfigMap approach seems cleaner for enabling both console and file appenders.\n\nI'm considering creating a custom log4j2.properties file to override the default Docker configuration, which only outputs to console. This would require adding another ConfigMap and volumeMount to the Elasticsearch container. However, I'm realizing that since containers in the same pod share the network namespace but not the logging namespace, I can't easily read one container's stdout from another container in the pod.\n\nThe better approach is to configure Elasticsearch to write log files to a shared volume instead. I'll create a ConfigMap with a custom log4j2.properties that enables JSON file logging, mount it in the Elasticsearch container, and have it write logs to the shared `es-logs` volume. Then Filebeat can read those files directly.\n\nWriting log4j2 configuration... Configuring the rolling file appender's triggering policies and rollover strategy, setting it to rotate daily and when files exceed 128MB, then automatically delete old logs matching the cluster name pattern. Configuring the log file pattern with compression and setting up the root logger to route messages to console and both rolling appenders. I'm realizing the Docker image configuration might differ from the standard setup, so I should verify what's actually in the container's log4j2 properties file.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":577,"cache_read_input_tokens":57898,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":577},"output_tokens":19,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"53b80442-cd8b-488f-8175-b465ea97cfaf","uuid":"5924aa8e-9cd9-40d1-b27e-93ed29a9dad6","request_id":"req_011CcN685yTm8axgwKvkD2yR"}
