{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01J9XSLix83Zt2m3Q1cjTi8e","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see the log4j2.properties. All appenders are `Console` type, which means they output to stdout. I need to change the main `rolling` appender to write to a file instead of (or in addition to) the console.\n\nI'll create a custom log4j2.properties that changes the `rolling` appender to a `RollingFile` type that writes to `/usr/share/elasticsearch/logs/elasticsearch.json`. I'll keep the console appender as well so we don't lose stdout logging.\n\nThe plan:\n1. Create a ConfigMap with custom log4j2.properties\n2. Add a volumeMount in the elasticsearch container to mount it at `/usr/share/elasticsearch/config/log4j2.properties`\n3. The Filebeat sidecar will then read from the shared `es-logs` volume\n\nNow I'm modifying the log4j2.properties to change the `rolling` appender from `Console` to `RollingFile` type, configuring it to write to the elasticsearch logs directory while keeping console output intact.\n\nWriting log4j2 config... Writing logging configuration... Writing config properties...\n\nI'm realizing that the JVM properties like `es.logs.base_path` and `es.logs.cluster_name` are set by Elasticsearch at startup, so they should resolve correctly to the actual log directory path.\n\nNow I need to create a ConfigMap with the log4j2 configuration and add a volumeMount to the StatefulSet to use it, which will trigger another rolling restart to apply the new logging settings.\n\nI'm mounting the file at `/usr/share/elasticsearch/config/log4j2.properties` with a subPath to replace the default configuration. But I should verify whether the Elasticsearch Docker image uses `log4j2.docker.properties` instead, which could override my custom settings.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2408,"cache